column1: # This file contains fun numbers famous in sci-fi, internet memes, pop culture, geek subcultures and computing, used by the fun_number classifier.
# Add, edit, or remove entries as you like!

column2: Largest negative integer.
Zero; cardinality of the empty set; the additive identity; was represented using a shell in the ancient Mayan civilisation.
Number of dimensions we can see; number of particles generations in the standard model; first Mersenne prime.
Number of Platonic solids; number of vertices of a pyramid; number of vertices in the smallest non-planar (K5); the cycle of fifths underlies to musical harmonies; fifth Fibonacci number.
Considered a lucky or sacred number in many cultures and religions, often exaggerated in memes and fiction. '7 of 9' is a Star Trek: Voyager character (not literal, but often referenced numerically).
13—unlucky, also the number of colonies in Battlestar Galactica.

Sum of the first three squares, i.e. a square-pyramidal number; open meandric number: the number of meanders in non-self-intersecting oriented curves; number of pounds in one stone; fourth Catalan number.
Magic constant in a 3×3 magic square; largest composite number with one group of that order; triangular, hexagonal, pentatope and Bell number.
Only number of the form x y=y x with x and y distinct integers; number of pawns in a chess set, and each player starts with 16 pieces; length of credit card numbers.

Only non-zero number that is twice the sum of its digits; sum of the first three pentagonal numbers, making it a “pentagonal pyramidal number”; lucky number and the value for life in Jewish numerology.
Maximum number of 4th powers needed to sum to any number; number of cells in the only non-trivial magic hexagon.

Number of rooted trees with 6 vertices; number of faces of an icosahedron and vertices of a dodecahedron; number of quarter or half turns required to optimally solve a Rubik’s cube in the worst case; base of the ancient Mayan number system; sum of the first 4 triangular numbers, and thus a tetrahedral number.

Magic number in Blackjack; number of dots on a 6-sided die; smallest number of distinct squares into which a square can be dissected; smallest Fibonacci number whose digits and digit sums are also Fibonacci.
Number of partitions of 8; number of Major Arcana cards in divinatory Tarot; pentagonal and a centred heptagonal number.
23 enigma (Illuminatus! Trilogy, Lost, pop culture mysticism).
Largest number divisible by all integers less than its square root; only non-trivial integer n with the property that 1 2+…+n 2 is a perfect square; number of hours in a day.
Smallest nontrivial fifth power; 32=1 1+2 2+3 3; sum of the totient functions of the first ten integers; freezing point of water at sea level in Fahrenheit.
Largest integer that isn’t the sum of distinct triangular numbers; number of vertebrae in a human spine; sum of the first four factorials.
Smallest number that has the same number of divisors as the previous and following number; magic number of the order four magic square; nontotient and noncototient number.
Number of different hexominoes; sum of the first five triangular numbers; highly cototient and tetrahedral number.
Smallest non-trivial number which is both square and triangular; sum of the cubes of the first three integers; the sum of the first 36 integers is 666.
Maximum number of 5th powers needed to sum to any number; lucky, irregular, unique and cuban prime; human body temperature in degrees Celsius; number of plays written by Shakespeare.
Magic number of an order 3 magic hexagon; number of slots in American Roulette; largest even number which cannot be written as the sum of two odd composite numbers.
Sum of five consecutive primes: 3 + 5 + 7 + 11 + 13; sum the first three powers of three: 3 + 9 + 27; number of steps in the title of a Hitchcock film.
Only number whose letters are in alphabetical order; Venus returns to the same point in the night sky every 40 years; octagonal number; number of days in Lent.
The polynomial n^2+n+41 gives primes for n<40; lucky number of Euler, and the largest such prime; number of Mozart’s last symphony.
The Answer to the Ultimate Question of Life, the Universe, and Everything (Douglas Adams, The Hitchhiker’s Guide to the Galaxy).
Lowest atomic number of any element without stable isotopes; smallest prime that is not a Chen prime; smallest prime number expressible as the sum of two, three, four or five primes.
Star Trek writers' in-joke: number 47 appears frequently in the franchise.
Studio 54 (pop culture/celebrity hub).
Pop culture meme number (humor, innuendo). Also the largest factorial that fit calculators with 2-digit exponent: 70! ≈ 1.198×10^100: overflowed.
“The best number” (Sheldon, Big Bang Theory): 21st prime; 7×3=21, and 12 reversed is 21.
V.23/Minitel upstream serial baudrate (the famous 1200/75 split).
88 miles per hour—the speed needed for time travel (Back to the Future).
Number of graphic non-whitespace characters in ASCII; smith number, since the sum of its digits equals the sum of its prime factors; 94! – 1 is prime.
The decimal expansion of its reciprocal starts with the powers of two: 1/98=0.010204081632….
Agent 99 (Get Smart, classic spy comedy).
Boiling point of water in Celsius; denoted by the letter C in Roman numerals; sum of the first four cubes: 100=1^3+2^3+3^3+4^3.
Room 101 (Orwell's 1984); also 'Intro 101' as a code for basics in US education.
Number of heptominoes (one of which contains a whole); sacred number in the Dharmic Religions.
Teletype/ASR-33 era terminal baudrate; classic vintage UNIX console speed.
Magic constant of the smallest magic square composed only of prime numbers and 1; magic constant of a 6×6 magic square.
The emergency telephone number throughout the European Union and many other countries worldwide; equivalent to 911 in the US/Canada.
A113 was the Pixar animation classroom at the California Institute of the Arts.
Smallest number which can be written as the sum of three integers in four different ways, so that the product of every triple is the same
Smallest number that is the product of 7 prime factors (2 7); largest number that is not the sum of distinct squares; power of 2, all of whose digits are powers of 2
Smallest number that is the sum of all 2-digit numbers made from its digits; sixth Catalan number
Fine-structure constant — numerology or nature’s favorite number?
Sum of the cubes of its integers: 153=1 3+5 3+3 3; sum of the first 5 factorials and the first 17 natural numbers.
The boiling point of water in Fahrenheit.
221B Baker Street (Sherlock Holmes, referenced in Doctor Who and elsewhere).
largest number that can be represented using an 8-bit unsigned integer
Bell 103 acoustic-coupler modem baudrate—early BBS/‘WarGames’ dial-up vibes.
Pi (3.14), beloved in science/math pop culture.
Docking Bay 327 in Star Wars: A New Hope (Millennium Falcon arrival).
A common meme for 'not found' errors or missing content.
Internet meme and counterculture reference (esp. 4:20 PM as 'weed time').
the title of 'Fahrenheit 451', Ray Bradbury’s novel, named for the temperature at which book paper ignites.
The Number of the Beast: a beastly (or hateful) number from the Bible (Revelation), popular in pop culture, heavy metal, horror, and edgy memes.
The emergency telephone number in the US, Canada and several other countries; also associated with the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks in the US.
THX 1138 (George Lucas's first feature film and recurring Star Wars/Lucasfilm Easter egg).
Hayes Smartmodem baudrate; golden-age BBS calling with AT commands.
'Leet' speak for 'elite', iconic in hacker/gamer culture.
NCC-1701—registry number of the Starship Enterprise (Star Trek).
Nineteen Eighty-Four, classic dystopian novel (George Orwell).
2001 is the year featured in '2001: A Space Odyssey' by Arthur C. Clarke and Stanley Kubrick.
Rush concept album (sci-fi dystopia, cult favorite in geek culture).
Leia's cell number in Star Wars: A New Hope (cell 2187); also an homage to experimental film '21-87'
Number of pounds in an (English) ton.
Smallest number with 5 different prime factors.
Dial-up modem/BBS baudrate from the late ’80s file-swap era.
Equals 2^5×9^2 and is the only number with such a pattern.
Smallest number to appear 8 times in Pascal’s triangle (there is no other number less than 2^23 appearing 8 times).
The first four digits of pi (π = 3.141...) — math and pop culture symbol.
Number of seconds in one hour.
Largest number that can be written in Roman numerals, as MMMCMXCIX.
Intel 4004 — first commercially available microprocessor (1971).
Classic 4k demoscene size limit (and 2¹²).
GPS NMEA-0183 default serial baudrate (marine/nav gear staple).
The only square pyramidal number that is also a square: 4900=70^2=1^2+2^2+3^2+…+24^2
Mentioned by Plato as the ideal number of people living in a city, due to its high number of factors.
Sum of the first 7 factorials: 5913 = 1! + 2! + 3! + … + 6! + 7!.
MOS 6502 CPU (Apple II, Commodore, Atari) — iconic 8-bit era processor.
MOS 6510 CPU (Commodore 64).
equals 20^3, but is also the sum of four consecutive cubes: 11^3+12^3+13^3+14^3.
Intel 8086 CPU (x86 lineage begins here).
HAL 9000, sentient computer (2001: A Space Odyssey).
It's Over 9000!—internet meme from Dragon Ball Z.
Canonical serial console baudrate—‘9600 8N1’ everywhere (routers, printers, dev boards).
Number of hypercube unfoldings in 5D.
Largest number that cannot be represented as the sum of distinct cubes.
“PETSCII block” memory page nostalgia; 13,312 bytes free on some Commodore BASIC screens.
A Leet number: 'a Leeter' (playful extension of leet).
V.32bis modem/fax baudrate—‘14.4’ stuck in dial-up lore.
Largest number that is not the sum of the squares of distinct primes.
Common post-BBS serial console baudrate in industrial/embedded gear.
Jean Valjean's prisoner number (Les Misérables); geek culture references.
Number of possible Tic-tac-toe games.
MIDI protocol baudrate since 1983 (synths, drum machines, keyboards).
A Leet number: 'Eleet' or 'elite'; highly regarded in old-school hacker circles.
Commodore 64 Basic Bytes Free.
The maximum value for a signed 16-bit integer (2¹⁵–1); often seen as a classic data limit (e.g., MIDI, audio, legacy software).
2¹⁵ (midpoint of 16-bit range) — powers-of-two lore in computing.
The minimum value for a signed 16-bit integer (–2¹⁵); underflows/overflows in legacy software and hardware.
Classic UNIX/Linux/BSD serial console baudrate.
First number, other than 1, that is simultaneously triangular, pentagonal and hexagonal.
‘56K modem’ marketing-era baudrate (V.90/V.92 nostalgia).
Faster embedded/serial console baudrate; a stepping stone to 115200.
The maximum value for an unsigned 16-bit integer (2¹⁶–1); common as the highest port number (TCP/UDP), color depth, and memory limits in classic computing.
2¹⁶ — classic 16-bit boundary.
Motorola 68000 CPU (Amiga, Atari ST, Macintosh).
Registry of USS Voyager (Star Trek: Voyager).
ESP8266 boot ROM debug-log baudrate—quirky but famous in maker circles.
A calculator gag spelling of “BOOBS” upside-down.
Ubiquitous modern UART/USB-serial baudrate—Arduino/ESP/boot logs ‘hello world’.
A joke about weak passwords.
The Number of the Chosen: Sacred number, Iconic symbolic number appearing in cultural & religious contexts.
High-speed UART baudrate for faster flashing and logs.
Arduino/Marlin 3D-printer friendly baudrate (nice timer divisors on AVR).
First six digits of e — math/CS meme adjacent.
First six digits of π — nerd culture shorthand.
Very-high UART/debug baudrate used in performance-hungry pipelines.
Near-megabaud UART baudrate—common for fast firmware flashing.
Round 1M UART baudrate used by bootloaders and microcontrollers.
Mebibyte: 2^20; represents 1 MiB; fundamental computing threshold.
A calculator gag spelling "BOOBIES" upside-down.
Jenny's phone number (Tommy Tutone, iconic in pop culture).
A Leet number: 'Double leet'; playful combination of leet digits.
The maximum value for a 24-bit integer (2²⁴–1); classic color value in true color (24-bit, 16.7 million colors: #FFFFFF).
A Leet giggle; it combines meme numbers 1337, 69, and 420.
Speed of light in vacuum reached. All further classifiers are relativistic.
UNIX time for 13 Feb 2009 23:31:30 GMT (computer/geek humor).

The maximum value for a signed 32-bit integer; the largest representable Unix time (seconds since Jan 1, 1970) in 32-bit systems. Will cause the 'Year 2038 problem' or 'Unix Millennium Bug' when the counter overflows.
Number of hypercube unfoldings in 8D.
The maximum value for an unsigned 32-bit integer (2³²–1); appears in programming, file size limits, IP address space (255.255.255.255), and more.
The probability of receiving a complete suit in the game of Bridge.
The number of different Catan boardgames you can play.
Number of hypercube unfoldings in 9D.
The maximum value for a 48-bit integer (2⁴⁸–1); used in MAC addresses and classic computing boundaries.

The maximum value for an unsigned 64-bit integer (2⁶⁴–1); 'all bits set' in 64-bit computing. The number of grains of rice required if you place one grain on the first square of a chess board, two on the second, 4 on the third, 8 on the fourth, and so on.
Googor, named large number for 3^60.
Googolith, named large number for 2^100.
Googol, named large number for 10^100.
Googolex, named large number for 120^60.
Megiston, named large number for 2^512
Googoc, named large number for 200^100.
Googol-cube, named large number for 10^300.
Megiston, named large number for 10^303.
